izing the anti-modern positions of the Catholic Church. Drawing attention to the pervasiveness of anti-Catholic anticlericalism among Jewish thinkers and activists from the late eighteenth to the early twentieth century, the book turns the master narrative of Western and Central European Jewish history on its head. From the moment in which Jews began to enter the fray of modern European politics, they found that Catholicism served as a convenient foil that helped them define what it meant to be a good citizen, to practice a respectable religion, and to have a healthy family life. Throughout the long nineteenth century, myriad Jewish intellectuals, politicians, and activists employed anti-Catholic tropes wherever questions of political and national belonging were at stake: in theoretical treatises, parliamentary speeches, newspaper debates, the founding moments of the Reform movement, and campaigns against antisemitism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAnti-CatholicismxHistoryx19th centuryxFrance. 0aAnti-CatholicismxHistoryx19th centuryxGermany. 0aAnti-CatholicismzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aAnti-CatholicismzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aAnti-clericalismxHistoryx19th centuryxFrance. 0aAnti-clericalismxHistoryx19th centuryxGermany. 0aAnti-clericalismzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aAnti-clericalismzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewsxPolitics and governmentx19th centuryxFrance. 0aJewsxPolitics and governmentx19th centuryxGermany. 0aJewszFrancexPolitics and governmenty19th century. 0aJewszGermanyxPolitics and governmenty19th century. 4aFrench history. 4aGerman history. 4aJewish emancipation. 4aanti-Catholicism. 4aanticlericalism. 4aantisemitism. 4aliberalism. 4areligion. 4asecularism. 4atransnational history. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh08